Summary¶

To simplify some processes, we decided to use the open-source library PyTorch, which has useful tools for deep learning. Cifar-10 data can be downloaded through the library datasets module.

In possession of the dataset, initial procedures were performed. First, converting the format of the images through the transforms module included in the library, and then the normalization of the converted images. The normalization step was introduced given the behaviour of activation and loss functions. In other words, this functions perform better if your input is in the range [-1, +1]

In terms of implementation we created a class named CIFAR10TrainingModel. It has among others generic methods for loading, transforming and training a model. It's implemented on the cifar10_model.py file. The models used are implemented in the models.py file, and designed according to the PyTorch specification

The first model we trained was a simple neural network. With this approach we were able to achieve an accuracy on the validation data of around 40%. We them perceived that by using increasing the number of iterations on the the process we were overfitting the training model, that is, the accuracy on the training set was increasing, but the accuracy on the validation model was not improving or not improving at the same rate.

This distance between the validation accuracy and the training accuracy was our major way of identifying when our approach was overfitting the training data.

After this baseline we decided to try using a more sophisticated approach with an estabilshed model for convolutional neural networks, the LeNet model. Just by using this new model we were able to reach an accuracy of around 70% on the validation data. But after that we were overfitting.

This made us think of regularization techniques to try to prevent overfitting. Our approach was to use data augmentation. This made the accuracy on the validation set curve follow much closer the accuracy on the training one. But prevented the network from learning on the training set.

With this approach we reached the level of accuracy of around 63%

After this approach we tried using transfer learning through AlexNet. PyTorch makes it easy to use the ImageNet weights. Even though we were able to modify the model to the Cifar10 dataset, the computational perfomance requirements to train just the neural network portion of the AlexNet proved to be too high for our setup.

After this exploration we settled on using the LeNet model without image augmentation for the test dataset. And with this we achieved an accuracy of 73%

The Cifar10 dataset¶

The Cifar10 dataset consists of 50000 images for tranining and 10000 images for testing. The images are split in 10 different classes. They are in rgb and their size is 32x32

The dataset module of PyTorch is capable of download both sets.

Finding the mean and std of the training dataset¶

The images now have different intensity distributions. We would like that they would be normalized. This way our model could better associate a intensity, or relation of intensities with a given feature. Besides, activation and loss functions tend to perform better when the input is in the range [-1, +1].

To normalize the images we are going to iterate over the entire training dataset, and find the mean and std value for each color channel. Then we are going to normalize the entire training set according to this values. And we also need to trasform the images to tensors. This implies changing the dimensions of an image of 32x32x3, the format expected by utilities like plt.imshow to display images, to the format 3x32x32, the format that PyTorch expects for standard image training.

In terms of implementation, we already baked those numbers into the Cifar10TrainingModel class. But we repeat the implementation here for presentation purposes.

Partitioning the dataset¶

We are going divide the dataset into 4 distinct categories.

The first category consists of 40000 images. They will be used for training.

The second is a category of 100 images. This category will be used for the overfitting test.

The third category consists of 10000-100 images to be used for validation.

And the fourth and final category will be untouched throught the process. And is only going to be used once. For the final test after the model selection.

The overfitting test¶

The overfitting test is an implementation practice. It consists of overtraining your model on a single batch to see if your model has enough capacity to model a very simple subsection of your data. It is also very usefull to catch implementation bugs. We decided to leave the implementation of the overfitting test into different files. But we did it for all of the models tested. Reaching close to or perfect accuracy on all the models explored. The files that implement the overfit test have an overfit on their name

The baseline¶

To establish the baseline we tried a very simple and shallow neural network. It consists of two linear layers with 50 neurons in between. It uses the hyperbolic tangent function as activation. And, like all the other models presented, uses the cross entropy loss function.

For optimization we used the Adam optimizer with an initial learning rate of 1e-3. The use of Adam instead of SGD makes the initial choice of learning rate less important, since it uses a form of adaptive learning rate during training.

Comparing the perfomance of the LeNet model with our baseline, we first note that by the first iteration this model was already better than the baseline at the last iteration. That is, here we started with around 55% accuracy on the validation set, while the last iteration on the baseline barely passed 40% on the same set.

Nevertheless, this model also had the same problem, overfitting. After the fourth iteration the curves started diverging, and our validation accuracy improved at a much slower rate, reaching 73% accuracy after 10 iterations, with a 87% accuracy on the training set.

LeNet with data augmentation¶

To prevent overfitting we decided to explore the data augmentation technique. The exact transformations can be seen in the next cell. But the main idea is to generate more images for training by injecting some form of random noisy transformation that keeps the data recognizable.

In [44]:
lenet_aug_model = CIFAR10TrainingModel(model=LeNet(),
                             learning_rate=1e-3,
                             optimizer=optim.Adam,
                             loss_fn=nn.CrossEntropyLoss())
lenet_aug_model.load_and_transform_data(transform_list=transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.RandomAffine(0, shear=10, scale=(0.8,1.2)),
        transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=1, contrast=1, saturation=1),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize((0.4915, 0.4823, 0.4468),
                             (0.2470, 0.2435, 0.2616))
]))

By further training the LeNet model with data augmentation we saw that something was preventing the model from increasing it's accuracy on the training set. Transfer Learning¶

After the problem with data augmentation in the LeNet model we decided to try something different and explore transfer learning. PyTorch makes it easy to get the weights for built-in models. Hence, we decided to experiment with modifying the AlexNet model to classify images in the Cifar10 dataset.

The AlexNet model was trainined on the ImageNet dataset and famously won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge in 2012 by a large margin. The main difference with the previous is the sheer scale of the model. It's number of parameters dwarf's the previouly trained ones.

This number of parameters poses a great chalenge for training. It's much more computationaly expensive to train the model. To remedy this we can freeze a part of the network with previously trained weights, here in another dataset, and make small tweaks in the model to fit a new dataset.

But even after fixating the majority of the parameters in the network our current computational setup was unable to train the model. Each epoch of training was taking longer than 1 hour. This made tweaking our implementation quite hard. And we decided to focus on the other models of the project.

Nevertheless, the implementation is working, and with further exploration we believe that it could achieve a much higher generalization than the other models.

Therefore we present here the overfitting test for the implementation, and show the previous aborted results.

In [59]:
from torchvision.models import AlexNet_Weights
from torchvision import models
alex_net = models.alexnet(AlexNet_Weights)
# Here we fix the features that will not be trained
for param in alex_net.features.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

# We also need to modify the final layer of the model. To output a 10-d vector instead of a 1000-d one.
n_inputs = alex_net.classifier[6].in_features
last_layer = nn.Linear(n_inputs, 10)
alex_net.classifier[6] = last_layer
alex_net_model = CIFAR10TrainingModel(model=alex_net,
                                      learning_rate=1e-4,
                                      optimizer=optim.Adam,
                                      loss_fn=nn.CrossEntropyLoss())

alex_net_model.load_and_transform_data(transform_list=transforms.Compose([
    # And resize the input to what AlexNet was trained on
    transforms.Resize((224, 224)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize((0.4915, 0.4823, 0.4468),
                         (0.2470, 0.2435, 0.2616))
]))

n_epochs = 5
alex_net_model.overfit_single_batch(n_epochs)

Model selection and test accuracy¶

In terms of the model selection we decided to base our decidion on the accuracy over the validation set. The main discussion was if the generalization found by training the LeNet model with data augmentation could be a better fit for unseen data. But since it's accuracy on the validation set was still significant lower than wihout data augmentation. We decided to do it without.

Conclusion¶

We explored explored different models for the problem of image classification into the classes defined in the Cifar10 dataset.

We first estabilished a baseline using a simple neural network, achieving around 40% accuracy on the validation set. The training, however, was overfitting the training set, thus preventing further epochs from increasing the accuracy.

After that we used the LeNet model and achieved an accuracy of around 70%. But the problem of overfitting remained an issue.

To prevent overfitting we tried using data augmentation with the LeNet model. This did prevent overfitting, but it came at the cost of increasing the training accuracy.

We then tried using transfer learning by modifying AlexNet. This, however, proved to be computationaly unfeasible for our setup.

After this we settled on using the LeNet model without data augmentation for the test dataset. And by using it we achieved 73% accuracy.
